{{For|the psychiatrist and psychoanalyst|Herbert Sullivan (psychiatrist)}}
{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}
{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}
[[File:Bertie and arthur sullivan.jpg|thumb|right|Herbert Sullivan (right) with his uncle, [[Arthur Sullivan]], c. 1890]]
'''Herbert ('Bertie') Thomas Sullivan''' (13 May 1868 – 26 November 1928) was the nephew, heir and biographer of the British composer [[Arthur Sullivan]].  He grew up as his uncle's ward and worked briefly as an engineer.  After his uncle's death, Sullivan became active in charitable work. He was co-author of a 1927 biography of Arthur Sullivan, well regarded in its day, but later discredited because of its suppression of the composer's diary entries that mentioned his gambling and philandering.

Sullivan inherited many of his uncle's papers and original music manuscripts. Sullivan left most of these to his wife, who died in 1957, and they finally were sold to collectors in 1966.

==Biography==
Herbert Sullivan was the third child and eldest son of [[Fred Sullivan|Frederic]] and Charlotte Sullivan, one of eight siblings.{{refn|His brothers and sisters were: Amy Sophie (1863–1947), Florence Louise (1865–1891), Edith Mary (1866–1877), Maud "Cissie" Helen (1870–1940), [[Frederic Richard Sullivan]], George Arthur (1874–1919) and William Lacy (1877–1902).|group= n}} When Fred Sullivan died aged 39 in 1877, his younger brother, the composer [[Arthur Sullivan]], made himself responsible for the support of Fred's widow and eight children. In 1881, Charlotte married Captain Benjamin Hutchinson, a man 13 years her junior.<ref>Hayes (2002), pp. 6–8</ref> Charlotte emigrated to the US in 1883 with her husband and all her children except Herbert, who remained in England under the care of his uncle.{{refn|Charlotte died in January 1885, barely a year after the move to California. Hutchinson, unable to cope with this loss and his responsibilities, soon returned to England, leaving the six surviving California children (Edith had died) to be raised mostly by their uncle William Lacy, with the financial support of their uncle Arthur.<ref>Hayes (2002), pp. 10–12</ref>|group= n}} At the age of nine, Sullivan began boarding school in [[Brighton]], England.<ref>Ainger, p. 135</ref> He studied in Germany in the autumn of 1884.<ref>Jacobs, p. 197</ref>

Arthur Sullivan's health was precarious from the 1880s onwards, and Herbert often accompanied his uncle to the [[South of France]] and other resorts where the composer rested or spent holidays.<ref>''[[The Times]]'', 8 April 1892, p. 9</ref> In late 1890, at 22 years of age, Herbert left his uncle's home for an engineering job connected with the laying of a cable between Haiti and Brazil.<ref>Ainger, p. 323</ref> Herbert soon returned to England, and he continued to spend much of his time with his uncle, continuing as his companion at the theatre and on trips. Though never formally adopted, Herbert was in many respects Arthur Sullivan's adopted son. He was at his uncle's bedside at his death in 1900.<ref name=Sherr>Sherr, Richard. ''Journal of the American Musicological Society'', Vol. 38, No. 3 (Autumn, 1985), pp. 637–43</ref> When Arthur died, the German Emperor [[William II, German Emperor|Wilhelm]], an admirer of Sullivan's works, sent Herbert a personal message of condolence.<ref>''The Times'', 27 November 1900, p. 11</ref> Herbert remained friendly with his uncle's collaborator, [[W. S. Gilbert]], after Arthur's death; when Herbert organised a [[Garrick Club]] dinner in 1908, in honour of Gilbert, the dramatist wrote, "My dear Sullivan, There is little need to tell you how deeply I appreciate the good feeling that actuated you in organizing yesterday's most successful dinner. It is an instance of friendship that can never fade from my memory".<ref>Letter from Gilbert to Herbert Sullivan, 4 October 1908, reproduced in Dark and Grey, p. 198</ref>

[[File:Newman-Flower.jpg|thumb|right|upright|[[Newman Flower]] in 1917]]
After his uncle's death, Herbert Sullivan inherited the bulk of the composer's estate, including his diaries and many of his important musical manuscripts. He became prominent in ''pro bono publico'' activities, and in April 1915 he contributed the manuscript of ''[[Utopia Limited]]'' by [[Gilbert and Sullivan]] to a charity auction in aid of the [[Red Cross]].<ref>''The Times'' 27 April 1915, p. 11</ref> During the First World War, Herbert became a [[King's Messenger]]. While in this service, his ship was hit by a torpedo, and he spent hours in the freezing waters of the North Sea. Afterwards, he found walking painful and used a cane.<ref>Hayes (2009), p. 58</ref> While on his yacht ''Zola'', in 1921, he retrieved mail from the [[English Channel]] after an aeroplane crash.{{refn|On 26 August 1921, Sullivan [[1921 SNETA Farman Goliath ditching|witnessed the crash]] of a [[Farman F.60 Goliath|Farman Goliath]] aircraft of [[SNETA]] into the English Channel off [[Calais]], France, while sailing ''Zola''. He reported the crash and retrieved a bag of mail from the sea.<ref>"Wreck of an Air Mail", ''The Times'', 27 August 1921, p. 9</ref>|group= n}} In 1923 he married Elena Margarita Vincent.<ref>[http://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?cite=%2FLeaGRWSLNBL3ic8hmlLAg&scan=1 Marriages registered in April, May & June 1923], freebmd.org.uk</ref> He served as Warden of the [[Worshipful Company of Musicians]] in 1925 and as Master of the Company in 1926.

In 1927 Sullivan collaborated with [[Newman Flower]] on a biography of Arthur Sullivan. As Sullivan and Flower had exclusive access to the composer's diaries, the biography was regarded at the time as uniquely authoritative. Subsequently, when wider access to the diaries became possible, it was seen that Sullivan had suppressed mention of his uncle's gambling and womanising, and this evasion, combined with the lack of musical analysis in the biography, led to a lowering of its status among scholars.<ref name=Sherr/>

Herbert Sullivan died suddenly in London in 1928, aged 60.  His estate included many of his uncle's manuscripts. His widow remarried about 1929, becoming Mrs Elena M. Bashford.<ref>''The Times'', 5 December 1929, p. 17</ref> She died in 1957,<ref>Allen, p. xvii</ref> and the manuscripts were sold at auction in 1966 by her estate, some going to museums and collectors in America and others remaining in England.<ref>''The Times'' 14 June 1966, p. 12</ref> Several of the autograph scores were bought by the [[Gilbert and Sullivan]] scholar and collector [[Terence Rees|Dr Terence Rees]] and others by dealers.<ref>A list of the sales is found in ''The Gilbert and Sullivan Journal'', vol. 9, no. 3, September 1966, p. 44</ref>

