'''Nazperver Kadın''' ({{lang-ota|نازپرور قادین}}; 12 June 1870 &ndash; 9 March 1929; born '''Princess Emine Çikotua'''),{{sfn|Açba|2007|p=171}} meaning "Breeder of grace",<ref>{{cite book|first=Halide Edib|last=Adıvar|title=Inside India|publisher=K.N. Book House|year=2009|pages=143|isbn=}}</ref> was the fourth wife of Sultan [[Mehmed V]] of the [[Ottoman Empire]].{{sfn|Uluçay|2011|p=261}}{{sfn|Sakaoğlu|2008|p=703}}

==Early life==
Nazperver Kadın was born on 12 June 1870 in [[Beşiktaş]], [[Istanbul]]. Born as Emine Çikotua, she was a member of an [[Abkhaz people|Abkhazian]] princely family Çikotua.  Her father waas Prince Ismail Bey Çikotua, and her mother was Princess Aliye Hanım Dziapş-lpa, the daughter of Prince Mahmud Dziapş-lpa. She had a sister named Behiye Hanım. She was the maternal niece of [[Dürrünev Kadın]], first wife of Sultan [[Abdülaziz]].{{sfn|Açba|2007|p=171-2}} 

In 1874, Emine had been brought to [[Istanbul]] as a young child, where her father entrusted her and her sister to the care of her aunt Dürrünev Kadın. her name according to the custom of the Ottoman court was changed to Nazperver.{{sfn|Açba|2007|p=172}}

Abdülaziz was deposed by his ministers on 30 May 1876, his nephew [[Murad V]] became the Sultan.<ref>{{cite book|first=Erik J.|last=Zürcher|title=Turkey: A Modern History, Revised Edition|publisher=I.B.Tauris|year=October 15, 2004|pages=73|isbn=978-1-850-43399-6}}</ref> He was transferred to [[Feriye Palace]] the next day.<ref>{{cite book|first1=Stanford J.|last1=Shaw|first2=Ezel Kural|last2=Shaw|title=History of the Ottoman Empire and Modern Turkey: Volume 2, Reform, Revolution, and Republic: The Rise of Modern Turkey 1808-1975, Volume 11|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=1976|pages=164|isbn=978-0-521-29166-8}}</ref> Her aunt Dürrünev, and other women of Abdülaziz's entourage didn't wanted to leave the Dolmabahçe Palace. So they were grabbed by hand and were send out to the Feriye Palace. In the process, they were searched from head to toe and everything of value was taken from them.{{sfn|Brookes|2010|p=40}} Naperver followed her aunt to Feriye Palace.{{sfn|Açba|2007|p=172}} On 4 June 1876,<ref>{{cite book|first=Roderic H.|last=Davison|title=Reform in the Ottoman Empire, 1856-1876|publisher=Princeton University Press|year=December 8, 2015|pages=341|isbn=978-1-400-87876-5}}</ref> Abdülaziz died under mysterious circumstances.{{sfn|Brookes|2010|p=43}}

==Marriage==
One day, when Mehmed was in his forties, he visited aunt-in-law Dürrünev Kadın in the Feriye Palace. Here he saw Nazperver, then eighteen years old, and fell in love with her. He asked his aunt-in-law to give him Nazperver in marriage. She acceded to her nephew-in-law's demand, and the marriage took place in 1888 in the Veliahd Palace.{{sfn|Açba|2007|p=172}} Nazperver didn't bore Mehmed any children.{{sfn|Brookes|2010|p=286}} 

On 27 April 1909, after Mehmed's accession to the throne,<ref>{{cite book|first=Suraiya|last=Faroqhi|title=The Cambridge History of Turkey|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=2008|pages=79|isbn=978-0-521-62096-3}}</ref> she was given the title of "Dördüncü Kadın". Upon the death of [[Dürrüaden Kadın]] in October 1909, Nazperver was given the title of "Üçüncü Kadın".{{sfn|Uluçay|2011|p=261}}{{sfn|Sakaoğlu|2008|p=703}} 

Safiye Ünüvar, a teacher at the [[Palace School]], who met her in 1915, described her as being plump, and tall.<ref>{{cite book|author=Uniwersytet Jagielloński. Instytut Filologii Orientalnej|title=Turks and non-Turks: studies on the history of linguistic and cultural contacts|year=2005|publisher=Institute of Oriental Philology Jagiellonian University|page=524|isbn=978-83-7188-891-5}}</ref> According to Ünüvar, Nazperver did not appeared particularly learned, but she did had a refined and kindly air about her that made a good impression. It seems that having no children weighed heavily upon her, despite the fact that the Sultan treated her most kindly and graciously, and so she lived out her life in this rather downhearted fashion.{{sfn|Brookes|2010|p=210}}

On 18 May 1918, Nazperver met with the Empress [[Zita of Bourbon-Parma]] in the Dolmabahçe Palace, when the latter visited Istanbul. During the Empress's visit, she communicated with her in French,<ref>{{cite book|first=Leyla|last=Açba|title=Bir Çerkes prensesinin harem hatıraları|year=2004|publisher=L & M|pages=56|isbn=978-9-756-49131-7}}</ref>{{sfn|Açba|2007|p=173}} which she had been taught by her aunt Dürrünev Kadın.{{sfn|Açba|2007|p=172}}

==Death==
After Mehmed's death on 3 July 1918,<ref>{{cite book|first=Spencer C.|last=Tucker|title=World War I: The Definitive Encyclopedia and Document Collection [5 volumes]: The Definitive Encyclopedia and Document Collection|publisher=ABC-CLIO|year=October 28, 2014|pages=1071|isbn=978-1-851-09965-8}}</ref> Nazperver settled in a mansion at Vaniköy,{{sfn|Sakaoğlu|2008|p=703}} where she died on 9 March 1929. She was buried in Yahya Efendi Cemetery, [[Istanbul]].{{sfn|Açba|2007|p=174}}

