{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}} {{Use British English|date=April 2012}} {{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] --> | name = Sarah Fuller Adams | image = SarahFlowerAdams.jpg | imagesize = 200px | caption = Sketch of Sarah, after an 1834 sketch by [[Margaret Gillies]] | pseudonym = S.Y.<ref name="Orlando">Brown, Susan, Patricia Clements, and Isobel Grundy, eds. Sarah Flower Adams entry: Life screen within ''Orlando: Women's Writing in the British Isles from the Beginnings to the Present''. Cambridge: Cambridge University Press Online, 2006. http://orlando.cambridge.org/. 28 November 2018.</ref> | birth_name = Sarah Fuller Flower | birth_date = {{Birth date|1805|2|22|df=yes}} | birth_place = [[Old Harlow]], [[Essex]], [[England]] | death_date = {{Death date and age|1848|09|14|1805|2|22|df=yes}} | death_place = [[London]], England | resting_place= [[Foster Street]], Essex, England | nationality = British | language = English | occupation = Poet, hymnwriter | period = | notableworks = "[[Nearer, My God, to Thee]]" | awards = | spouse = {{marriage|[[William Bridges Adams]]|1834}} | children = | relations = [[Benjamin Flower]], [[William Fuller (banker)|William Fuller]], [[Richard Fuller (died 1782)|Richard Fuller]], [[Eliza Flower]], [[Richard Flower (settler)|Richard Flower]], [[John Clayton (minister)|John Clayton]] | signature = Sarah Adams signature.png }} '''Sarah Fuller Flower Adams''' (or '''Sally Adams'''<ref name="Orlando"/>) (1805 – 1848) was an [[England|English]] poet and [[hymnwriter]], best known for writing the words of the hymn "[[Nearer, My God, to Thee]]".<ref name = Blain>{{cite|first =Virginia H.|last=Blain|article=Adams, Sarah Flower (1805–1848)|title=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2004|url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/129|access-date=3 November 2017}}</ref>
==Early years and education== Sarah Fuller Flower was born 22 February 1805, at [[Old Harlow]], [[Essex]],{{sfn|Hatfield|1884|p=1}} and baptised in September 1806 at the Water Lane Independent Chapel in [[Bishops Stortford]].<ref>{{cite|title = FamilySearch|url = https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:NPSW-JMN |access-date = 4 October 2015}}</ref> She was the younger daughter of the radical editor [[Benjamin Flower]],{{sfn|Julian|1892|p=16}} and his wife Eliza Gould.<ref name = Blain/>
Her father's mother Martha, sister of the wealthy bankers [[William Fuller (banker)|William Fuller]] and [[Richard Fuller (died 1782)|Richard Fuller]], had died the month before Adam's birth. Her elder sister was the composer [[Eliza Flower]].<ref name = Blain/><ref>{{cite book | last = Hale | first = Sarah Josepha Buell | authorlink = Sarah Josepha Hale | title = Woman's Record; Or, Sketches of All Distinguished Women, from the Beginning... | publisher = Harper & bros | year = 1853 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=13UEAAAAYAAJ}} 874 pp.</ref> Her uncles included [[Richard Flower (settler)|Richard Flower]], who emigrated to the United States in 1822 and was a founder of the town of [[Albion, Illinois]];{{sfn|Hatfield|1884|p=4}} and the nonconformist minister [[John Clayton (minister)|John Clayton]].
Her mother died when she was only five years old and initially her father, a liberal in politics and religion,{{sfn|Hatfield|1884|p=2}} brought the daughters up, taking a hand in their education. The family moved to [[Dalston]] in [[Middlesex]], where they met the writer [[Harriet Martineau]], who was struck by the two sisters and used them for her novel “Deerbrook”. In 1823, on a holiday in [[Scotland]] with friends of the radical preacher [[William Johnson Fox]], the minister of South Place Unitarian Chapel, London, who was a frequent visitor to their home, Adam broke the female record for climbing up [[Ben Lomond]]. Back home, the girls became friends with the young poet [[Robert Browning]], who discussed his religious doubts with Adam.<ref name = Blain/>
==Career== After the father's death, about 1825, the sisters became members of the Fox household.{{sfn|American Unitarian Association|1922|p=1094}} Both sisters began literary pursuits, and Adam first fell ill with what became [[tuberculosis]]. Soon after, the sisters moved to [[Upper Clapton]], a suburb of [[London]]. They attached themselves to the [[Conway Hall Ethical Society|religious society]] worshipping in South Place, [[Finsbury]], under the pastoral care of Fox. He encouraged and sympathized with the sisters, and they in turn helped him in his work. Eliza, the elder, devoted herself to enriching the musical part of the Chapel service, while Adams contributed hymns.{{sfn|American Unitarian Association|1922|p=1094}} Fox was one of the founders of the ''[[Westminster Review]]''.{{sfn|Hatfield|1884|p=2}} and his Unitarian magazine, the ''[[Monthly Repository]]'', printed essays, poems and stories by [[William Bridges Adams]], polemicist and railway engineer, who Adam met at the house of her friend, the feminist philosopher [[Harriet Taylor Mill]]. The two married in 1834,<ref name = Blain/> setting up house at [[Loughton]] in Essex. In 1837, he distinguished himself as the author of an elaborate volume on ''English Pleasure Carriages'', and another on ''The Construction of Common Roads and Railroads''. He was also a contributor to some of the principal reviews and newspapers.{{sfn|Hatfield|1884|p=2}}
Encouraged by her husband, Adams turned to acting and in the 1837 season at [[Richmond, London|Richmond]] played [[Lady Macbeth]], followed by [[Portia (The Merchant of Venice)|Portia]] and [[Lady Teazle]], all successes. Though offered a role at [[Bath, Somerset|Bath]], then a springboard for the [[West End theatre|West End]], her health broke down and she returned to literature.<ref name = Blain/>
In 1841, she published her longest work, ''Vivia Perpetua, A Dramatic Poem''. In it, a young wife who refuses to submit to male control and renounce her [[Christian]] beliefs is put to death. She contributed to the ''Westminster Review'', including a critique of [[Elizabeth Barrett Browning]]'s poetry, and wrote political verses, some for the [[Anti-Corn Law League]]. Her work often advocated equal treatment for women and for the working class.{{Citation needed|date=April 2018}} At the solicitation of her pastor, she also contributed thirteen hymns to the compilation prepared by him for the use of his chapel, published 1840-41, in two parts, six in the first and seven in the second part. Of these, the two best known —" Nearer, my God! to Thee," and "He sendeth sun, he sendeth shower"— are in the second part. For this work, her sister, Eliza, wrote sixty-two tunes. Her only other publication, a catechism for children, entitled "The Flock at the Fountain," appeared in 1845.{{sfn|Hatfield|1884|p=3}} Her hymn, "Nearer, my God! to Thee", was introduced to American Christians in the "Service Book," published (1844) by Rev. James Freeman Clarke, D.D., of [[Boston]], [[Massachusetts]], from where it was soon transferred to other collections.{{sfn|Hatfield|1884|p=4}} A selection of hymns she wrote, published by Fox, included her best-known piece, "Nearer, My God, to Thee", reportedly played by the band as the [[RMS Titanic]] sank in 1912.<ref name = Blain/><ref>{{cite web| title = Titanic's Band | url = http://www.titanic-titanic.com/titanic_band.shtml |publisher= Titanic-Titanic |accessdate=3 April 2013}}</ref>
==Personal life== A Unitarian in belief, her career was hampered by deafness she had inherited from her father and, inheriting their mother's feebleness, both sisters yielded to disease in middle age. Eliza, after a lingering illness, died in December 1846 and, worn down by caring for her invalid sister, Adam's health gradually declined. She died on 14 August 1848 at the age of 43 and was buried beside her sister and parents in the Forest Street cemetery near Harlow.{{sfn|Hatfield|1884|p=3}}{{sfn|Hatfield|1884|p=4}}<ref name = Blain/>{{sfn|Julian|1892|p=16}} At her grave was sung the only other hymn of hers which was widely known, “He sendeth sun, he sendeth shower”.{{sfn|American Unitarian Association|1922|p=1094}}
A [[blue plaque]] honouring the husband and wife was placed at their Loughton home: they had no children. [[Richard Garnett (writer)|Richard Garnett]] wrote of her:— "All who knew Mrs. Adams personally speak of her with enthusiasm; she is described as a woman of singular beauty and attractiveness, delicate and truly feminine, high-minded, and in her days of health playful and high-spirited."[https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/Adams,_Sarah_Flower_(DNB00)]
==Selected works== {{div col|colwidth=30em}} *"Nearer, my God, to Thee" *"He sendeth sun, he sendeth shower" *"Creator Spirit! Thou the first. Holy Spirit." *"Darkness shrouded Calvary. Good Friday." *"Gently full the dews of eve. Evening." *"Go, and watch the Autumn leaves. Autumn." *"O hallowed memories of the past. Memories." *"O human heart! thou hast a song. Praise." *"O I would sing a song of praise. Praise." *"O Love I thou mabest all things even. Love." *"Part in Peace! Is day before us? dote of Service." *"Sing to the Lord! for His mercies are sure. Praise." *"The mourners came at break of day. Baxter." {{div col end}}
